+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01DfreLbCZim8BEpYEB9dh5u","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/**\n     2→ * Format a Date object to an ISO date string (YYYY-MM-DD).\n     3→ * Uses UTC methods to avoid timezone-related shifts.\n     4→ */\n     5→// TODO: fix timezone\n     6→export function formatDate(date: Date): string {\n     7→  const year = date.getUTCFullYear();\n     8→  const month = String(date.getUTCMonth() + 1).padStart(2, '0');\n     9→  const day = String(date.getUTCDate()).padStart(2, '0');\n    10→  return `${year}-${month}-${day}`;\n    11→}\n    12→\n    13→/**\n    14→ * Parse an ISO date string (YYYY-MM-DD) into a Date object.\n    15→ * Creates the date in UTC to avoid timezone issues.\n    16→ */\n    17→export function parseDate(str: string): Date {\n    18→  const [year, month, day] = str.split('-').map(Number);\n    19→  return new Date(Date.UTC(year, month - 1, day));\n    20→}\n    21→\n    22→/**\n    23→ * Get the start and end dates for a given month.\n    24→ * Returns ISO date strings for the first and last day of the month.\n    25→ */\n    26→export function getMonthRange(year: number, month: number): { start: string; end: string } {\n    27→  const start = new Date(Date.UTC(year, month - 1, 1));\n    28→  const end = new Date(Date.UTC(year, month, 0)); // last day of the month\n    29→  return {\n    30→    start: formatDate(start),\n    31→    end: formatDate(end),\n    32→  };\n    33→}\n    34→\n    35→/**\n    36→ * Check if a date string falls within a range (inclusive).\n    37→ */\n    38→export function isDateInRange(date: string, start: string, end: string): boolean {\n    39→  return date >= start && date <= end;\n    40→}\n    41→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze e